  "local_port": 40126,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does a non-US citizen/resident  search for jobs in US?",
  "response": "Searching for jobs in the US as a non-US citizen/resident involves several steps, including understanding visa requirements, leveraging online resources, and networking. Here\u2019s a comprehensive guide to help you navigate the process:\n\n1. **Understand Visa Requirements:**\n   - Research the various types of work visas available, such as the H-1B, L-1, O-1, and J-1 visas.\n   - Determine which visa category you qualify for and understand the application process and timeline.\n\n2. **Prepare Your Documents:**\n   - Update your resume/CV according to US standards, highlighting your skills, experience, and education.\n   - Write a tailored cover letter for each job application.\n   - Gather necessary documents like academic transcripts, letters of recommendation, and any professional certifications.\n\n3. **Online Job Portals:**\n   - Use job search engines and websites like LinkedIn, Indeed, Glassdoor, Monster, and USAJOBS (for government positions).\n   - Set up job alerts to receive notifications about new job postings that match your criteria.\n\n4. **Company Websites:**\n   - Visit the careers pages of companies you\u2019re interested in. Many companies post job openings directly on their websites.\n   - Research companies known to sponsor work visas, such as tech giants, consulting firms, and global corporations.\n\n5. **Networking:**\n   - Connect with professionals in your industry via LinkedIn and ask for informational interviews.\n   - Join online communities and forums related to your field.\n   - Attend virtual career fairs, webinars, and industry conferences.\n   - Utilize alumni networks from your educational institutions.\n\n6. **Recruitment Agencies:**\n   - Partner with recruitment agencies that specialize in placing international talent or have experience with visa sponsorship.\n\n7. **Professional Associations:**\n   - Join professional associations and organizations related to your field in the US. They often have job boards and networking events.\n   \n8. **Internships and Fellowships:**\n   - Consider applying for internships or fellowships, some of which may offer sponsorship opportunities for non-US citizens.\n\n9. **Tailor Your Applications:**\n   - Customize each job application to match the job description and company culture.\n   - Highlight any international experience and language skills, which can be advantageous for certain roles.\n\n10. **Prepare for Interviews:**\n    - Practice common interview questions and research the companies thoroughly.\n    - Be prepared to discuss your visa status and any sponsorship requirements.\n\n11. **Understand Employment Laws:**\n    - Familiarize yourself with US employment laws, including workers\u2019 rights and obligations.\n\n12. **Check Visa Sponsorship:**\n    - Ensure that the companies you apply to are willing to sponsor visas for international employees.\n\nBy following these steps, you can enhance your chances of finding a job in the US. Good luck with your job search!",
